****Poisson Distribution

Is a descrete probability distribution that expresses the probability of a given number of events occuring in a fixed interval of time
or space if these events occur with a known constant rate and independently of the time since the last event [13]. 

The poisson Distribution applies when:

1. The event os something that can be counted in integers
1. Occurrences are independent, so that one occurrence neither deminishes nor increases the chance of another
1. the average frequency of occurance for the time period is known,and:
1. It is possible to count how many events have occured

It most commenly used for rare events [14]

>>> import numpy as np
>>> s = np.random.poisson(5, 10000)
Display histogram of the sample:

>>>
>>> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
>>> count, bins, ignored = plt.hist(s, 14, density=True)
>>> plt.show()


Hypergeometric Distribution

Used to calculate the statistical significance of having drawn specific *k* successes (out of *n* draws) from the population. It is 
often used to identify which sub-populations are over- or under-represented in the sample [15]. An example of the Hypergeometric
distribution

It is used in which selections are made from two groups without replacing members of the group. It is often  employed in random sampling
for statistical quality control.

>>> ngood, nbad, nsamp = 100, 2, 10
# number of good, number of bad, and number of samples
>>> s = np.random.hypergeometric(ngood, nbad, nsamp, 1000)
>>> hist(s)
#   note that it is very unlikely to grab both bad items

>>> s = np.random.hypergeometric(15, 15, 15, 100000)
>>> sum(s>=12)/100000. + sum(s<=3)/100000.
#   answer = 0.003 ... pretty unlikely!




